{{Infobox book| | name = Last Words | title_orig = | translator = | image = Last Words by George Carlin.jpg | caption = | author = [[George Carlin]] with [[Tony Hendra]] | cover_artist = | country = United States | language = English | series = | subject = [[Autobiography]] | genre = [[Non-fiction]] | published = November 10, 2009 [[Free Press (publisher)|Free Press]] | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]]) | pages = 320 | isbn = 1-4391-7295-1 | preceded_by = [[Three Times Carlin: An Orgy of George]] }}
'''''Last Words''''' is the [[autobiography]] of American [[Stand-up comedy|stand-up comedian]] [[George Carlin]].<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=120502583| title=Comedian George Carlin's 'Last Words'| publisher=National Public Radio| date=November 17, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/nov/28/entertainment/la-et-book28-2009nov28| author=Steve Appleford| title='Last Words' by George Carlin| publisher=Los Angeles Times| date=November 28, 2009}}</ref> It was published on November 10, [[2009 in literature|2009]]. ''Last Words'' tells the story of his life from his conception, literally, to his final years; he died on June 22, 2008 at the age of 71. He also wrote a special parting gift to the world. The book contains photos taken throughout Carlin's life.
In 1993, George Carlin asked his friend and bestselling author [[Tony Hendra]] to help him write his autobiography, although Carlin called it a "sortabiography".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://articles.washingtonpost.com/2009-12-29/news/36846900_1_george-carlin-al-sleet-autobiography| author=Jeff Nussbaum| title=George Carlin, daring and delightful to the end| publisher=The Washington Post| date=December 29, 2009}}</ref> The two of them had scores of conversations, many were recorded, for almost fifteen years. During the conversations, they discussed Carlin's life, times, and evolution as a major comedian artist. After Carlin died, Hendra set out to assemble the book just as Carlin would have wanted.{{citation needed|date=March 2014}}
This book was also released twice in [[Audiobook]] format. The first recording at unabridged length narrated by Johnny Heller and the second with George's brother Patrick reading an abridgment.
