{{refimprove|date=September 2010}}
An '''Organist and Master of the Choristers''' is a title given to a [[Director of Music]] at a [[cathedral]], particularly a [[Church of England]] cathedral. The tradition dates back to the Middle Ages. They are often both the [[organist]] and the [[choirmaster]].

As Organist and Master of the Choristers, they are primarily occupied with the training and conducting of the cathedral choir. The sub-organist or assistant organist usually plays at cathedral services, although they will also be expected to take over the choral duties if the organist is unavailable.

One of the longest serving Organist and Master of the Choristers was Andrew Goodwin, who retired from [[Bangor Cathedral]] on 31 October 2009. He had served there for 37 years. He was the master of the choristers when [[Aled Jones]] was in the choir.{{citation needed|date=September 2012}} Other long-serving holders of the title include Charles J Brennan who spent 60 years (1904-1964) at [[St Anne's Cathedral, Belfast|Belfast Cathedral]].<ref>http://www.newulsterbiography.co.uk/index.php/home/viewPerson/1820</ref>

